worth, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1327–":"about 1327–Deceased","1327–Female":"1327–Deceased","1329–1369":"1329–1369","1330–1418":"1330–1418","1329–1376":"1329–1376","1343–1405":"1343–1405","1360–Male":"1360–Deceased","1302–1349":"1302–1349","1305–1368":"1305–1368","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1305":"1305","1349":"1349","1327":"1327","1369":"1369","1368":"1368","1302":"1302","about 1327":"about 1327","about 1328":"about 1328","1343":"1343","1376":"1376","about 1343":"about 1343","1418":"1418","1329":"1329","about 1340":"about 1340","1405":"1405","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Chesworth, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Braose","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Eckhard, Gerhard, Manfred, Otto.","German:","from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Ambrosius</i> (see   Ambrose  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Braus","meanings":["German: variant of   Brause   2 ‘noise, roar’."]},{"name":"Ambrose","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the personal name <i>Ambrose</i> (French <i>Ambroise</i>, Latin <i>Ambrosius</i>, from Greek <i>ambrosios</i> ‘immortal, divine’), which was popular throughout Christendom in medieval Europe. Its popularity was due in part to the fame of Saint Ambrose (<i>c.</i> 340–397), one of the four Latin Fathers of the Church, the teacher of Saint Augustine. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Czech, Slovenian, and Croatian <b>Ambrož</b> (see   Ambroz  ), and also their derivatives, e.g. the Slovenian patronymic <b>Ambrožič</b>.","Irish: from <b>Mac Ambróis</b> ‘son of Ambrose’ (see 1 above); a West Munster name, which has also been Anglicized as   McCambridge  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes de Braose was born about 1327, in Sussex, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir John de Braose, was 27 and her mother, Margaret Trehampton, was 24. She married Urian de Sancto Pierre about 1340, in Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1327–":"umbes 1327–Surnud","1327–Female":"1327–Surnud","1329–1369":"1329–1369","1330–1418":"1330–1418","1329–1376":"1329–1376","1343–1405":"1343–1405","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1302–1349":"1302–1